<P>Bards receive a mix of musical, fighting, and miscellaneous skills. I didn’t 
include the ones common to all classes such as alcohol tolerance or pottery. 
<P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Level 1 Skills</B></FONT><P><P>
<UL>
  <LI>1h Blunt, 2h Blunt – These two skills are better for classes which lack 
  slashing, namely clerics and int-based spell casters. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>1h Slashing – This should be your weapon category of choice as a Bard. The 
  Minotaur Axe, located on a small percentage of Minotaurs in Steamfront, should 
  be a Bard’s first good weapon. Expect to come in possession of this around 
  level 8 or 9.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>2h Slashing – Although available for Bards, there doesn’t seem to be any 
  two handed slashing weapons that Bards can use. Perhaps one will be added in 
  an update or expansion pack. Don’t worry too much about this category right 
  now because you cannot even practice the skill in combat, and will be at a 
  very low skill level when coming into possession of such a weapon.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Piercing – This fighting skill is mainly for magic users and Rouges. 
</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Throwing – Good, if expensive, for luring monsters from a distance. 
  Throwing weapons are a poor substitute for a bow. Examples of throwing objects 
  are throwing knives and shrukens.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Hand to Hand – Very important because bards can still punch when playing 
  instruments. This skill will be worthless during your first ten or so levels. 
  Most Bards, as a result, neglect keeping up with hand to hand skills. This can 
  be disastrous because it will be nearly impossible to improve your hand to 
  hand against the monsters of your level if your score remains at zero. Gaining 
  skills is only possible when fighting monsters that give experience. 
  Consequentially, characters don’t even have the option to go slaughtering 
  weaker monsters in order to raise certain skills. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Singing – This Bard only skill helps allows songs to be sung, and enhances 
  the effectiveness of those songs as the skill increases. Bards will be singing 
  during most of their play, so this song will max out early after a new level 
  is reached. </LI></UL>
  <P><FONT SIZE=3 COLOR=#FF6600><B>Level 5-40 Skills</B></FONT><P><P>
<UL>
  <LI>Percussion (L5) - This skill is one of four instrument based skills that 
  enhance certain songs when being played. The instrument that checks the 
  percussion skill is the drum.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>String (L8) – Strings is the second of four instrument-based skills. The 
  most notable song, Hymn of Restoration, will double in power when playing a 
  string based instrument such as a Mandolin. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Dodge (L10) – This skill offers a small chance at completely avoiding the 
  enemy’s attack. During combat, it will say, "Creature has tried to slash YOU, 
  but you DODGE!".</LI>
  <LI>Brass (L11) – The third of four instrument skills that enhances certain 
  songs. The Horn is the instrument that calls on this skill.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Forage (L12) – The chance at gathering free food and water is a real nice 
  skill. Wood Elves automatically receive this skill at level one, but the other 
  two Bard races will catch up at level 12. This skill is more useful at newbie 
  levels when the small cost of food and drink takes a sizable bite into their 
  bank accounts. It’s still quite a nice skill at the higher levels, especially 
  when lost in new lands. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Wind (L14) – The last of four instrument based skills, which utilizes the 
  flute, which enhances certain songs.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Dual Wield (L17) – The ability to wield two weapons simultaneously is one 
  of the best fighting skills in the game! Bards get this ability a few levels 
  after Warriors, but it’s still just as useful. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Sneak (L17) - walk past enemies undetected. Currently useless versus other 
  players. Characters are still visible when sneaking, they just don’t make 
  noise. </LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Safe Fall (L24) – Safe fall gives the ability to drop from great heights 
  without taking damage.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Hide (L25) – Players cannot be attacked or seen while hidden. Enemies with 
  ‘see invisible’ cast upon them will still notice a hidden character. Hide also 
  doesn’t work on a creature that is already aggressive towards that 
  character.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Instill Doubt (L26) – A successful install doubt will cause the target to 
  turn around and walk away. For some reason, this skill can only be trained 
  with Caskin Marsheart, who is located on second floor of the Freeport bard 
  guild.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Disarm traps (L30) – There aren’t many traps in Everquest, so this skill 
  isn’t that useful.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Track (L35) – This great skill allows hunting desired monsters very 
  easy.</LI></UL>
<UL>
  <LI>Pick locks (L40) - Like traps, there aren’t many of them in the world. 
  This can be useful in dungeons, but some of those locks cannot be picked. 
</LI></UL>
<P></FONT>&nbsp;</P>


